{"active_answer": "Yukimura Haruki, Nureki Chimuo or Marai Masato", "active_index": 684, "active_question": "Which three individuals are cited as examples of old-school style tyers?", "audit_index": 15, "decision": "drop", "document_sha256": "821a4f5fac301d0698c6d5aad8cb152d00d1fbbb3bbc077c0fac760417e625ca", "fact_id": "fact-1263411b5e120944bb5b", "reason": "A stylistic name list in a commercial vertical-suspension tutorial announcement is subjective and lacks durable explanatory value.", "reason_code": "volatile_or_promotional", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v17", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 7, "bare_answer_points": 0, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 11, "risk_score": 0, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v17", "source": "esinem", "source_document": "data/raw/esinem_4cdf0843c58d3796.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "3e4c4033ef051737b548938abeb41740a4a6451a617d6e7e287627489ab6e66e", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "Part VII builds on the skills that you have gained in previous tutorials in the ‘Tying techniques’ series to learn how to tie a hashira shibari suspension, i.e. on a vertical beam or post. This is a classic method of tying, especially with those tying in the old-school style like Yukimura Haruki, Nureki Chimuo or Marai Masato, because it uses the traditional architecture of old Japanese houses, wooden beams which would commonly present themselves.", "support_evidence_sha256": "2828ac8045888716ba04436bb2b9d46d092a324e9348addc010c7281ccb83024", "url": "https://www.esinem.com/hashira-shibari-vertical-beam-suspension-tutorial/"}
{"active_answer": "the society for the study of beautiful bondage", "active_index": 247, "active_question": "What is the English translation of the Japanese term 'Kinbakubi kenkyūkai'?", "audit_index": 16, "decision": "keep", "document_sha256": "0285b78a2c4cfdd3aac800435828b225bca90e48c877517bcf6d26e3c48c0677", "fact_id": "fact-9ad07ddb01e5389309a3", "reason": "The source directly translates a historically named study group and situates its continuation and lineage.", "reason_code": "kinbaku_history_term_context_complete", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v17", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 8, "bare_answer_points": 0, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 11, "risk_score": 0, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v17", "source": "kinbakutoday", "source_document": "data/raw/kinbakutoday_f6ccdaa49bed3fa5.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "31df3f1ad06d2a04da434818b6894f2bd1b481b142400997ddd07ec0a04dd086", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "On December 4th, I had the pleasure of visiting Naka Akira’s second meeting of Kinbiken. The group takes it name from a shortened version of 緊縛美研究会, or “Kinbakubi kenkyūkai” which translates to something like “the society for the study of beautiful bondage.” The meeting is a continuation of a series of gatherings started in 1986, led by Nureki Chimuo, Naka sensei’s teacher and mentor.", "support_evidence_sha256": "e727d89be9151ebacf47fd1986375a12a9cf33fab14eeb1909d15532f4897678", "url": "https://www.kinbakutoday.com/visiting-kinbiken-remembering-nureki/"}
